==English==

===Etymology===
{{bor|en|fro|beverage}}, variant of {{m|fro|bevrage}}, from {{m|fro|beivre||to drink}}, variant of {{m|fro|boivre||to drink}}, from {{der|en|la|bibō}}. Related to {{m|en|imbibe}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-beverage.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{IPA|/ˈbevəɹɪdʒ/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
[[File:Drinks at a buffet in the Pan-European University, Bratislava, Slovakia - 20140723.jpg|thumb|A selection of beverages at a buffet in {{w|Bratislava}}, {{w|Slovakia}}]]
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|chiefly|_|American}} A [[liquid]] to [[consume]], usually excluding [[water]]; a [[drink]]. This may include tea, coffee, liquor, beer, milk, juice, or soft drinks.
#* Thomson
#*: He knew no '''beverage''' but the flowing stream.
# {{lb|en|slang|archaic}} A [[treat]], or [[drink]] [[money]].

====Usage notes====
More elevated than plainer {{m|en|drink}}. '''Beverage''' is of French origin, while {{m|en||drink}} is of Old English origin, and this stylistic difference by origin is common; see {{w|list of English words with dual French and Anglo-Saxon variations}}.

